Preliminary Analysis:
In Preliminary Analysis, we will be taking a look at the DataSets and a High-Level Reasoning for the Data Cleansing & Data Massaging to Extract Impactful Information:
  • Assessment of the City specific DataSets needs granularity in Date for extracting and disseminating context-specific Information efficiently, hence we are extracting the [YEAR] and [MONTH] into separate columns.
  • Setting up Colour Palettes for different data points enables better Human-Readable Information from the Deluge of Raw Data.
  • Pre-Processing and Pre-Filtering Raw data makes it more malliable to work with to produce Information,while costing minimal processing overhead. 
# Extracting Month and Year from Time for better processing
datasets <- list("MAA", "BLR", "DEL", "LKO", "BOM", "JDH", "BBI")

# Adding 2 extra columns [MONTH] & [YEAR] to the City Dataset for making filtering easier.
for (dataset in datasets)
  {
  assign(dataset, get(dataset) %>%
           mutate(
             time = as.Date(time, format = "%d-%m-%Y"),
             month = format(time, "%b"),
             year = as.numeric(format(time, "%Y"))
           )
        )
  }

city_day <- city_day %>%
  mutate(year = lubridate::year(Date))

# Create a color palette
color_palette <- c(
  "Bengaluru" = "#FF0000",
  "Bangalore" = "#FF0000",
  "Chennai" = "#0000FF",
  "Delhi" = "#00FF00",
  "Lucknow" = "#FFFF00",
  "Mumbai" = "#FF7F00"
)

# Define colors for AQI_Bucket categories
aqi_colors <- c(
  "Good" = "lightgreen", 
  "Satisfactory" = "yellow", 
  "Moderate" = "orange", 
  "Poor" = "red", 
  "Very Poor" = "purple", 
  "Severe" = "maroon"
)

# Define a vector of custom colors for each year
prcp_colors <- c(
  "#FF0000", "#FF0044", "#FF0088", "#FF00CC", "#FF00FF",
  "#FF4400", "#FF4444", "#FF4488", "#FF44CC", "#FF44FF",
  "#FF8800", "#FF8844", "#FF8888", "#FF88CC", "#FF88FF",
  "#FFCC00", "#FFCC44", "#FFCC88", "#FFCCCC", "#FFCCFF",
  "#FFFF00", "#FFFF44", "#FFFF88", "#FFFFCC", "#CCFFFF",
  "#CCFF00", "#CCFF44", "#CCFF88", "#CCFFCC", "#CC8800",
  "#CC8844", "#CC8888", "#CC88FF"
)

# Create a bird color palette
bird_color_palette <- c(

# Filter for 2021 and add city column for each dataset

LKO_2021 <- LKO %>% filter(year == 2021) %>% mutate(city = "Lucknow")
BOM_2021 <- BOM %>% filter(year == 2021) %>% mutate(city = "Mumbai")

# Combine all datasets into IND
IND <- bind_rows(MAA_2021, BLR_2021, DEL_2021, LKO_2021, BOM_2021)

# Filtering out Chennai AQI Stations
MAA_Stations <- stations %>%

1. Interactive Metropolitan City Map: 
# Create a map with markers for each city
leaflet(GEOLOC %>% filter(Location_Name %in% c("Bangalore", "Chennai", "Delhi", "Lucknow", "Mumbai")), 
        options = leafletOptions(minZoom = 4, maxZoom = 5)) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    ~Longitude, ~Latitude, 
    color = ~as.character(ifelse(Location_Name %in% names(color_palette), color_palette[Location_Name], "black")), 
    popup = ~paste0("<b>", Location_Name, "</b><br>Elevation: ", Elevation, "</br>")
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    colors = ~ifelse(Location_Name %in% names(color_palette), color_palette[Location_Name], "black"), 
    labels = ~ifelse(Location_Name %in% names(color_palette), Location_Name, "Other"),
    opacity = 1, position = "bottomright"
  )
We will be mainly focusing on these Metropolitan Cities and their weather track record.
2. AQI Distribution by City [2015 - 2020]: 
# Remove records where AQI is missing
city_day_clean <- city_day %>%
  filter(!is.na(AQI) & AQI != "") %>%
  filter(City %in% c("Bengaluru", "Chennai", "Delhi", "Lucknow", "Mumbai"))

# Plot a violin graph with custom colors
ggplot(city_day_clean, aes(x = City, y = AQI, fill = City)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000)) +  # Set max y-axis to 1000
  scale_fill_manual(values = color_palette) +  # Use the custom color palette
  labs(title = "AQI Distribution by City [2015 - 2020]", x = "City", y = "AQI") +
  theme_dark()

Here we have a Violin Plot showcasing the data-spread of AQIs for each city.
3. Total Precipitation per Month by City [2021]: 
# Group the data by month and city, then sum the precipitation
total_prcp_per_month <- IND %>%
  group_by(month, city) %>%
  summarise(total_prcp = sum(prcp, na.rm = TRUE)) # Remove NA values if any

# Ensure the month column is ordered
total_prcp_per_month <- total_prcp_per_month %>%
  mutate(month = factor(month, levels = c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
                                          "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec")))

# Create the bar plot
ggplot(total_prcp_per_month, aes(x = month, y = total_prcp, fill = city)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") + # Stack the bars by city
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(color_palette), name = "City") + # Add the color palette
  labs(
    title = "Total Precipitation per Month by City [2021]",
    x = "Month", 
    y = "Total Precipitation (mm)",
    fill = "City"
  ) +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Precipitation across the Months from each City in 2021.
4. Monthly Temperature Distribution Across Cities [2021]: 
# Mutate and order the data based on Month & perform pivot_longer to segregate the Tmin, Tavg, Tmax
IND_long <- IND %>%
  mutate(month = factor(month, levels = c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", 
                                            "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", 
                                            "Nov", "Dec"))) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(tmin, tavg, tmax), 
               names_to = "Temperature_Type", 
               values_to = "Temperature") 

# Create the box plot
ggplot(IND_long, aes(x = month, y = Temperature, fill = Temperature_Type)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  facet_wrap(~ city) +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(
    title = "Monthly Temperature Distribution Across Cities [2021]",
    x = "Month",
    y = "Temperature (C)",
    fill = "Temperature Type"
  )

An insightful look into the wild temperature differences across Metropolitans in India.

9. AQI Bucket Distribution for Chennai [2015 - 2022]: 
# Count the occurrences of each AQI_Bucket
aqi_counts <- MAA_AQI_Day %>%
  count(AQI_Bucket) %>%
  mutate(percentage = n / sum(n) * 100)

# Define the order of AQI_Bucket
aqi_order <- c("Good", "Satisfactory", "Moderate", "Poor", "Very Poor", "Severe")

# Ensure the AQI_Bucket is in the correct order
aqi_counts$AQI_Bucket <- factor(aqi_counts$AQI_Bucket, levels = aqi_order)

# Create the pie chart
ggplot(aqi_counts, aes(x = "", y = percentage, fill = AQI_Bucket)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1, color = "#000000") +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = aqi_colors) +
  scale_x_discrete(NULL, breaks = NULL) +
  scale_y_continuous(NULL, breaks = NULL) +
  theme_dark() +
  labs(title = "AQI Bucket Distribution for Chennai [2015 - 2022]") +
  theme(legend.position = "right") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "AQI Bucket"))

An insightful Pie-Chart showcasing the AQI of Chennai during the majority of its time between [2015] to [2022].

A line plotted datagraph showing the number of confirmed Avians per species visiting Pallikaranai Marshland.
Outcomes:
1.In this interactive map, we understand the geographical location of all the Metropolitan Cities we intend to scrutinize the data for deriving meaningful information.
  1. The Violin Plot helps us condense the large raw AQI dataset into clearly understandable/human-readable information. We have five cities included in the graph. From just a glance, we can determine that during the years [2015] to [2020] Mumbai had the least polluted air overall, closely followed by Bangalore & Chennai. But the AQI for Delhi and Lucknow is all over the place, mostly trending towards the Very Poor AQI Bucket.
  1. This Bar Graph helps us visualize the Precipitation of each city in the year 2021 across various months. Mumbai contributes the bulk of precipitation among the cities between the months of May to Sept.They experience the least rainfall in March and the most rainfall during July. Chennai & Bangalore seemingly rely on the Monsoon Season for receiving the bulk of their precipitation.
  1. This insightful look into the temperature differences using the boxplot across Metropolitans for the year [2021] shows us the temperature swings experienced by each city. Chennai shows the least variance in temperatures throughout the year whereas Delhi shows extreme swings in temperature, closely followed by Lucknow. Bangalore and Mumbai are neck and neck in the middle of the pack showing very similar temperature delta over the year [2021].
  1. These yearly AQI graphs solely focus on the 5 days flanking Diwali of that year. The adverse impact of explosives-laced celebrations is felt consistently the worst in Chennai as it goes from an AQI of Satisfactory straight to Severe consistently year on year. Delhi and Lucknow seem to be lost causes whereas Bangalore and Mumbai hold their own relatively well. This indicates Chennai can do with significantly tightening its belt on the fireworks each year in order to curb sharp spikes in AQI w.r.t Diwali celebrations.
  1. Another Interactive Leaflet Map showcasing the various points of interest, denoting the presence of an active AQI station. This Map focuses solely on the Greater Chennai Area for a focused understanding of the dynamics at play here.
  1. Month-wise Precipitation in Chennai gives us a strategic understanding of predicting Rainfall in this region. We have data points starting from [1990], up to [2022]. From the Plot Graph, we can easily infer that Chennai gets the least rainfall during the month of May and expects the most rainfall during Oct/Nov monsoon seasons.
  1. This boxplot shows us the Tmin, Tavg and Tmax of all the days in the years [1990] and [2021], month-wise. It is crystal clear to us that [2021] is a solid few degrees hotter than [1990]. It also doesnt get as code as [1990] during the Jan period. This shows us a clear-cut example of global warming affecting the temperatures of this city.
  1. The Pie-Chart gives us the AQI Buckets between the year [2015] to [2022]. We can quickly infer that Chennais AQI generally hovers around Satisfactory and Moderate. This isnt too unmanageable but is a clear warning sign to start taking action to mitigate the quality of air in and around Greater Chennai.
  1. Last but not least we have a line plotted datagraph showing the number of confirmed Avians per species visiting Pallikaranai Marshland. The data points extend from 1990 all the way up to 2022. This graph confirms the unfortunate reality that the wetlands have been absolutely devastated by illegal encroachment, garbage dumping and sewage poisoning taking place on a regular basis. Most species, prior to the 2000s, had healthy migratory patterns that included the key junction, Pallikaranai, we driven to near extinction lasting till 2010 due to lack of awareness. Now in recent years, due to the revival effort in place by the government and NGOs, the wetlands have a renewed and thriving population of avians. Though it is not yet to the level of pre 1990s, the recovery in population paints a positive outlook for the future.
Results and Discussions:
Between 2015 and 2020, Mumbai consistently had the least polluted air, followed by Bangalore and Chennai, while Delhi and Lucknow exhibited erratic and poor AQI levels, often in the Very Poor category. Chennai experiences sharp AQI spikes during Diwali due to fireworks, while Delhi and Lucknow face persistently severe pollution year-round. Rainfall patterns in 2021 show Mumbai receiving peak precipitation from May to September (highest in July) and Chennai relying on October-November monsoons. Temperature trends in 2021 highlight extreme swings in Delhi and Lucknow, stable climates in Chennai, and moderate variations in Mumbai and Bangalore. Historical data from 1990 to 2022 underscores global warming effects in Chennai, with rising temperatures and consistent rainfall peaks. Chennais AQI largely hovers around Satisfactory and Moderate, while restoration efforts at Pallikaranai Marshland are reviving avian populations, though they remain below pre-1990 levels.

Key Points and Recommendations

  1. Air Quality: Delhi and Lucknow need urgent pollution control, and Chennai must curb Diwali-related AQI spikes.
  2. Rainfall Management: Mumbai requires flood control during peak rains, and Chennai should bolster monsoon drainage infrastructure.
  3. Global Warming: Rising temperatures demand sustainable policies to mitigate climate change.
  4. Ecological Restoration: Continued focus on Pallikaranai Marshland conservation is vital for ecological recovery.
  5. Public Engagement: Educate communities on pollution control, wetland conservation, and sustainable practices.
  6. Data Utilization: Leverage rainfall and AQI trends for better disaster management and urban planning.

Implementing these strategies can ensure cleaner air, better climate resilience, and sustainable urban and ecological development.
